1
00:00:01,431 --> 00:00:30,713
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambhodassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambhodassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambhodassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble.

2
00:00:31,047 --> 00:00:35,731
and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:36,253 --> 00:00:46,444
I thought this evening to wander around this notion, this understanding of not-self and ethics.

4
00:00:50,247 --> 00:00:52,871
The Buddha belonged to what's known as the Axial Age.

5
00:00:53,911 --> 00:00:58,978
It's quite a lift in terms of human consciousness at the time, 2,500 years ago.

6
00:00:59,616 --> 00:01:02,159
So we have Confucius and Lao Tzu.

7
00:01:02,881 --> 00:01:09,429
Confucius turned what was empty ritual into something meaningful, coming from the heart.

8
00:01:10,570 --> 00:01:25,489
Moses, of course, got rid of all these mammon and stuff like that, established a single god, but most of all, an ethical code, which wasn't based on the power of gods or trying to appease gods or anything like that.

9
00:01:26,599 --> 00:01:37,435
And then you have Socrates, of course, at the same time, who brought rationality to the fore, undermining superstition, stuff like that.

10
00:01:37,454 --> 00:01:55,019
And in the Buddha's own country, people like Magantha and others who were really trying to investigate consciousness, which was, I think, more of an Indian thing than

11
00:01:55,507 --> 00:02:10,109
rather than to do with relationship to the world, although of course it came about, it was, I think, a peculiar investigation by Indians into what was consciousness as such.

12
00:02:11,951 --> 00:02:19,263
And so he belongs to that sort of rise of understanding in human society.

13
00:02:19,323 --> 00:02:22,407
Of course, even today, not many of us have...

14
00:02:23,062 --> 00:02:28,770
have risen to that, but at least it stands as a sort of standard where we can aim.

15
00:02:33,395 --> 00:02:47,872
In the Buddha's time, the distinction between the world and consciousness wasn't so objective as we might, I think, think these days through our scientific revolution, where the West

16
00:02:50,080 --> 00:03:00,412
pulled rationality completely out of its connection with the heart and created this very scientific way of looking at the world.

17
00:03:00,431 --> 00:03:07,300
And, of course, we've got all our knowledge from it, all these subatomic physics and stuff like that, and the technology that goes with it.

18
00:03:07,659 --> 00:03:09,782
But there's a loss of connection to the heart.

19
00:03:10,824 --> 00:03:15,348
And the first people who revolted against that, of course, were the romantics.

20
00:03:15,368 --> 00:03:16,509
You know, people like...

21
00:03:17,485 --> 00:03:19,427
Jean-Jacques Rousseau and Schelling.

22
00:03:19,728 --> 00:03:21,790
Is he a romantic?

23
00:03:21,811 --> 00:03:22,091
Schelling.

24
00:03:22,330 --> 00:03:23,612
And Wordsworth people.

25
00:03:24,533 --> 00:03:32,925
They all rebelled against this hard science which really understood the universe as some sort of mechanic, a car.

26
00:03:36,550 --> 00:03:38,092
Everything was like a jigsaw.

27
00:03:38,111 --> 00:03:39,614
All you had to do was fit it out.

28
00:03:39,734 --> 00:03:40,514
It was a machine.

29
00:03:40,855 --> 00:03:44,621
God became the God outside the machine that he'd created.

30
00:03:45,842 --> 00:03:46,462
And...

31
00:03:47,707 --> 00:03:55,082
The Buddha himself stands within a tradition which is not so technological.

32
00:03:55,584 --> 00:03:58,088
I mean, you know, still carts and oxes and all that.

33
00:03:59,031 --> 00:04:01,014
All his imagery is about agriculture.

34
00:04:02,878 --> 00:04:09,092
But this huge interest in consciousness and what that meant.

35
00:04:09,426 --> 00:04:17,899
And I think in those days, as I think it was for the ancients, even Socrates, I'm not sure he made such a distinction, but I don't know.

36
00:04:18,701 --> 00:04:25,331
But the world as we experience it is the only world that consciousness can offer us.

37
00:04:25,872 --> 00:04:32,502
So through the mind and body, whatever we're aware of is, as far as we're concerned, the world.

38
00:04:33,262 --> 00:04:38,690
We might think that the world exists out there or know through science that the world exists out there.

39
00:04:39,262 --> 00:04:46,812
There's meant to be light years away, all these planets and stuff like that, and galaxies and solar systems.

40
00:04:46,833 --> 00:04:48,475
But actually, we don't know that.

41
00:04:49,276 --> 00:04:53,762
We don't know that by our personal direct experience.

42
00:04:53,783 --> 00:04:56,086
And indeed, neither do scientists.

43
00:04:56,127 --> 00:04:58,529
What they get is light from who knows when.

44
00:05:00,473 --> 00:05:02,315
They only presume that it's carrying on.

45
00:05:03,004 --> 00:05:05,951
Might have all finished light years ago.

46
00:05:06,872 --> 00:05:12,043
So the Buddha's not really concerned with that sort of thing.

47
00:05:12,685 --> 00:05:18,798
There's a telling passage where somebody asks him, where does the world come to an end?

48
00:05:20,322 --> 00:05:21,925
Where does the world come to an end?

49
00:05:22,367 --> 00:05:22,987
And he said,

50
00:05:23,795 --> 00:05:25,476
That's not rightly put.

51
00:05:25,757 --> 00:05:27,819
That's not the right question to ask.

52
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:33,324
He says the question that should be asked is, where does the world not find a footing?

53
00:05:34,646 --> 00:05:36,108
That's a completely different question.

54
00:05:37,228 --> 00:05:51,303
And what he's pointing to is a level of awareness or an attainment of an awareness which doesn't belong to the world.

55
00:05:51,891 --> 00:05:56,899
So what he means by the world is everything that the body, mind and heart can create.

56
00:05:57,860 --> 00:06:00,504
So it's everything you see and feel, etc.

57
00:06:02,307 --> 00:06:03,127
It's your thoughts.

58
00:06:03,468 --> 00:06:08,255
All that belongs to the world of present day consciousness, moment to moment consciousness.

59
00:06:09,197 --> 00:06:11,500
And he's saying that there's something that transcends that.

60
00:06:12,963 --> 00:06:16,968
Not touched by any of it, not touched by any of the senses, including the mind.

61
00:06:17,870 --> 00:06:20,733
And he states this as, this is just the end of suffering.

62
00:06:22,266 --> 00:06:25,833
So why is it that ethics is so important?

63
00:06:26,353 --> 00:06:43,245
That's the question that really begs an answer because you might think well the enlightenment or the awakening rather is really just a matter of contacting this level and making it and holding it there and that's about it really.

64
00:06:44,795 --> 00:06:46,557
And that's the end of the job.

65
00:06:47,199 --> 00:06:54,028
So it's a process of just insight, just sitting, just keep looking, looking, looking, and eventually the penny will drop.

66
00:06:56,172 --> 00:07:11,494
But somehow he interlocks really deeply our whole behavior in terms of our thinking process, of how we relate to people, and so on and so forth.

67
00:07:12,975 --> 00:07:19,545
And this goes back to what's known as the three knowledges that came to him when he was awakened.

68
00:07:19,565 --> 00:07:22,891
The first one was that all the defilements had gone.

69
00:07:23,370 --> 00:07:25,353
He had no more defilements in his heart.

70
00:07:26,276 --> 00:07:28,017
So that's also an ethical statement.

71
00:07:29,279 --> 00:07:31,202
There was no defilement left in his heart.

72
00:07:31,223 --> 00:07:32,024
There was no anger.

73
00:07:32,064 --> 00:07:34,107
There was no all that sort of stuff.

74
00:07:36,348 --> 00:07:46,379
And then he said that he saw all a series of his past lives where he saw that they were driven by his ethical decisions.

75
00:07:49,101 --> 00:07:58,372
So in the three knowledges, his awakening is not described as some sort of way out state, blissed out and all that.

76
00:07:58,872 --> 00:08:00,353
It's telling you what there isn't there.

77
00:08:00,754 --> 00:08:03,076
And what there isn't there are these defilements.

78
00:08:03,538 --> 00:08:03,637
Okay?

79
00:08:04,461 --> 00:08:10,069
And then he says that these defilements were originally created by me through a series of lifetimes.

80
00:08:11,730 --> 00:08:19,920
And then the third one was that he saw beings moving from realm to realm dependent on their ethical decisions, their morality.

81
00:08:20,841 --> 00:08:24,105
So what was a personal law for him became a universal law.

82
00:08:24,846 --> 00:08:26,189
And he even included animals.

83
00:08:27,690 --> 00:08:33,658
Now that might be a bit strange to us, but there are clips on YouTube now

84
00:08:33,756 --> 00:08:39,884
Where, without any doubt, at least the higher animals do make ethical decisions.

85
00:08:40,645 --> 00:08:42,467
But maybe not quite as consciously as we do.

86
00:08:45,491 --> 00:08:50,857
Some of you might have got my news bite about the panther, the black panther.

87
00:08:51,119 --> 00:08:55,364
Did you get that?

88
00:08:55,384 --> 00:08:59,528
So, where does the problem of relationship begin?

89
00:09:00,049 --> 00:09:01,991
And how does it manifest?

90
00:09:02,258 --> 00:09:04,100
And how is it we get it wrong, you see?

91
00:09:06,485 --> 00:09:10,614
So the process that we're going through is twofold.

92
00:09:10,793 --> 00:09:14,280
We're actually trying to understand how we create this mess.

93
00:09:15,342 --> 00:09:25,160
And we're also going through a process of purification, where we begin to allow these defilements, that's what he calls them, defilements, to arise and pass away.

94
00:09:26,474 --> 00:09:31,740
And the process of insight meditation is that dual process.

95
00:09:31,779 --> 00:09:35,124
So it's not a process of developing the heart.

96
00:09:35,583 --> 00:09:39,668
That's done by other exercises such as metta, metta practice.

97
00:09:40,149 --> 00:09:44,274
And through action, through actions, compassionate, loving, joyful.

98
00:09:44,293 --> 00:09:45,014
Don't forget joy.

99
00:09:46,176 --> 00:09:47,498
Everybody talks about compassionate love.

100
00:09:47,518 --> 00:09:48,339
Forget joy.

101
00:09:49,980 --> 00:09:55,586
You can actually be joyful and rejoice in somebody else's joyfulness.

102
00:09:56,393 --> 00:10:00,438
That's also part of the Buddha mind that we're trying to develop.

103
00:10:00,458 --> 00:10:10,052
So this opening up to our own hearts in the meditation is part and parcel of allowing these defilements to go.

104
00:10:11,053 --> 00:10:22,110
In the Buddha's own experience, even though he was liberated during that moment, there was still what's known as vasana.

105
00:10:22,129 --> 00:10:26,316
Vasana are leftover habits within the mind.

106
00:10:27,730 --> 00:10:33,278
And so it is said that for seven years, Mara the evil one chased him with his three daughters.

107
00:10:35,061 --> 00:10:41,390
Sensual desire, sexual desire, and... Now those of you who know, you mustn't say.

108
00:10:41,951 --> 00:10:44,876
But those of you who don't know, what was the third one?

109
00:10:44,897 --> 00:10:45,376
Have a guess.

110
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:50,245
So there was sensual desire, sexual desire, and...

111
00:10:53,683 --> 00:10:54,404
Yes.

112
00:10:54,465 --> 00:10:54,926
Did you know?

113
00:10:54,946 --> 00:10:55,647
No.

114
00:10:55,667 --> 00:10:56,168
Well done.

115
00:10:56,408 --> 00:10:57,089
Fantastic.

116
00:10:57,789 --> 00:10:59,592
Very rare anybody gets that.

117
00:11:00,554 --> 00:11:01,316
Yes, and boredom.

118
00:11:01,856 --> 00:11:11,591
Because as we discussed this morning, boredom is the engine that pushes you to seek more and more excitement, seek something different to do.

119
00:11:12,212 --> 00:11:16,942
So, and it took seven years for these, for Mara to finally leave him, you see.

120
00:11:16,961 --> 00:11:18,585
His daughters insisted that.

121
00:11:18,985 --> 00:11:20,989
If they kept going, they'd get him.

122
00:11:21,389 --> 00:11:22,631
But he gave up.

123
00:11:22,652 --> 00:11:25,798
And what he says is, the Buddha sees me.

124
00:11:27,741 --> 00:11:29,244
See, the Buddha sees me.

125
00:11:29,445 --> 00:11:31,788
Now, of course, that's put in a mythological sense.

126
00:11:32,590 --> 00:11:35,115
When we, in our meditation...

127
00:11:35,736 --> 00:11:47,889
observe our defilements come up, be it their anger or something exciting or planning, just the seeing of them releases us from their grasp, just to be able to see them.

128
00:11:49,009 --> 00:11:59,880
This seeing, of course, also means to feel them, to actually experience them as they arise and pass away within that awareness, that consciousness.

129
00:12:02,123 --> 00:12:05,405
So we've got this...

130
00:12:06,870 --> 00:12:11,336
these mental defilements coming up, and they are habits.

131
00:12:11,437 --> 00:12:15,761
They are known as sankharas, habits that we have created ourselves.

132
00:12:16,523 --> 00:12:21,308
And the essential thing about the sankharas is that they are empowered through will.

133
00:12:22,129 --> 00:12:28,818
So the Buddha goes as far as to state that an act and the act of will, in his sense, are one and the same thing.

134
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:32,202
Will and an act are one and the same thing.

135
00:12:33,128 --> 00:12:42,736
So when we find ourselves thinking about something which is unpleasant, etc., and we're indulging in it, that's actually, there's got an act of will in there.

136
00:12:44,359 --> 00:12:46,701
And the same as when we speak something or when we act.

137
00:12:47,381 --> 00:12:55,129
And even when we do it unwittingly, even when we do it unintentionally, as it were, there's actually been a moment of intention.

138
00:12:56,431 --> 00:13:01,836
So we talk about habitual unethical actions and

139
00:13:02,153 --> 00:13:09,081
really empowered ethical action, when you really, really decide to murder your rival.

140
00:13:09,841 --> 00:13:14,427
That's a clear decision in time that you are actually going to murder them.

141
00:13:14,447 --> 00:13:17,331
Not that you do it sort of unintentionally.

142
00:13:19,813 --> 00:13:27,062
So often a lot of our thoughts that come up and we get dragged into are just because of these habits.

143
00:13:27,484 --> 00:13:31,148
And what we discover in our meditation, of course, is that they're incredibly powerful.

144
00:13:31,988 --> 00:13:38,076
And that even if we struggle against them, they're always there in the background.

145
00:13:38,836 --> 00:13:52,235
Even if we become acutely aware of our greed and stuff, there's always these little sneaky little selfishnesses where we take the biggest slice of cake and things like that.

146
00:13:52,716 --> 00:13:55,919
So these are very sneaky little things.

147
00:13:56,407 --> 00:14:04,154
And so the ability to actually see these things, you see, is a liberation.

148
00:14:04,274 --> 00:14:11,341
But remember, we're not entirely liberated from them because then there has to be the decision not to engage.

149
00:14:12,263 --> 00:14:23,815
And that's what we're learning through our meditation, that no matter what unethical thoughts or habits come up, we can distance from them and refuse to engage, right?

150
00:14:25,128 --> 00:14:31,953
Of course, the danger there is that in the refusal to engage, you're actually very subtly pushing them away.

151
00:14:32,815 --> 00:14:35,898
And we push things away out of aversion and fear.

152
00:14:36,839 --> 00:14:38,321
Those are our repressive measures.

153
00:14:40,022 --> 00:14:46,828
So one thing we come to be aware of is that there's an internal mechanism whereby we make things worse.

154
00:14:47,589 --> 00:14:53,514
So here comes the old greed, you see, and then there's the empowerment of the greed,

155
00:14:53,984 --> 00:14:56,668
by way of indulgence.

156
00:14:57,328 --> 00:15:04,839
Here comes a little sort of hateful thought about somebody and we empower it because we actually enjoy it.

157
00:15:04,859 --> 00:15:05,840
Yeah, of course we do.

158
00:15:06,240 --> 00:15:10,285
We enjoy getting angry with people and biffing them on the nose and things like that.

159
00:15:10,306 --> 00:15:11,628
There's a certain enjoyment in it.

160
00:15:12,089 --> 00:15:12,870
Otherwise we wouldn't do it.

161
00:15:14,369 --> 00:15:25,221
So when it comes to depression, we don't want to go into that sort of mental state, so we push it away, push it away by distracting ourselves.

162
00:15:25,241 --> 00:15:37,317
So a lot of the pleasures that we have in life are empowered not only because we enjoy them and indulge them, but because they're ways of not facing up to this other horrible stuff.

163
00:15:37,336 --> 00:15:41,000
And that's why addictions are so difficult to get rid of.

164
00:15:42,313 --> 00:15:44,296
And I'm not talking about big, heavy addiction.

165
00:15:44,336 --> 00:15:52,325
I'm just talking about, you know, biscuits and things like that.

166
00:15:52,345 --> 00:16:02,796
So, in a sense, when we understand that, you see, then we see where the struggle is, where when the Buddha's last words are, strive diligently.

167
00:16:02,816 --> 00:16:07,480
He doesn't say hang about and think about things and investigate.

168
00:16:07,740 --> 00:16:08,241
It's strive.

169
00:16:08,701 --> 00:16:10,924
Sampadeta is a very strong word.

170
00:16:10,985 --> 00:16:12,186
It's not sort of work at it.

171
00:16:12,740 --> 00:16:13,701
You've got to work at it.

172
00:16:14,302 --> 00:16:24,416
And you can see from our meditation that the work is not only something that you can do the once and then you'll never be greedy again.

173
00:16:24,475 --> 00:16:29,003
These snakes appear and crocodiles, they appear constantly.

174
00:16:29,222 --> 00:16:36,373
As soon as we see something that we have a relationship of indulgence with, then immediately the greed for it arises.

175
00:16:37,774 --> 00:16:42,662
So these sankaras, our internal habits,

176
00:16:42,962 --> 00:16:45,125
are really to be known.

177
00:16:45,365 --> 00:16:46,246
So that's what the Buddha says.

178
00:16:46,267 --> 00:16:48,970
You've got to know how they arise.

179
00:16:49,309 --> 00:16:52,854
You've got to know how to let them go and let them disappear.

180
00:16:53,254 --> 00:16:56,999
And you've got to know how, in such a way, that they never arise again.

181
00:16:57,019 --> 00:17:04,027
Of course, they never arise again until the deep fundamental problem is sorted out.

182
00:17:04,047 --> 00:17:05,628
And that's to do with identity.

183
00:17:07,364 --> 00:17:14,858
So in one way of looking at the path, it's put in these three different ways, sila, samadhi, and panya.

184
00:17:14,898 --> 00:17:19,268
Sila meaning morality, samadhi, concentration, and panya, insight.

185
00:17:20,289 --> 00:17:28,326
And it's funny that as he describes the Eightfold Path, he comes down from the insight path.

186
00:17:28,643 --> 00:17:30,365
and the insight becomes systemic.

187
00:17:31,226 --> 00:17:39,934
So once you have insight into, for instance, how indulgence creates suffering, this has to move into an attitude, right?

188
00:17:39,954 --> 00:17:41,777
That's your second on the Eightfold Path, right?

189
00:17:42,057 --> 00:17:43,679
Sammasankabha, right attitude.

190
00:17:43,919 --> 00:17:48,144
You've got to change your attitude to indulgence.

191
00:17:49,746 --> 00:17:51,968
Many, I mean, we...

192
00:17:52,910 --> 00:17:58,357
Noreen, whom some of you know, does a course, an email course.

193
00:17:58,377 --> 00:18:06,990
And there was one young fellow there who, the exercise was around seeing greed and whatnot.

194
00:18:07,772 --> 00:18:13,942
And one young fellow wrote back and said that once he'd begun to do this practice, he just wasn't enjoying things as he wanted to.

195
00:18:14,001 --> 00:18:14,963
So he wasn't ready for that.

196
00:18:15,544 --> 00:18:17,548
And he would stop the exercise.

197
00:18:17,768 --> 00:18:17,887
Right.

198
00:18:19,150 --> 00:18:24,116
It just shows how deep is our commitment to greed.

199
00:18:26,740 --> 00:18:33,391
And that commitment manifests also in all the other negative stuff too.

200
00:18:34,692 --> 00:18:40,622
So this sila, this morality in the path comes after that.

201
00:18:41,042 --> 00:18:42,505
It comes after right attitude.

202
00:18:42,565 --> 00:18:45,849
Then you get this right speech, right action and right livelihood.

203
00:18:46,386 --> 00:18:49,875
But the way that we can also see it is that you can go the other way.

204
00:18:50,356 --> 00:18:56,794
So you can start looking at our ethical behavior and that will also begin to change our attitude.

205
00:18:56,814 --> 00:19:01,265
The more we change our attitude, of course, it has to come back into the way we understand things.

206
00:19:01,285 --> 00:19:02,808
You can't change your attitude.

207
00:19:03,008 --> 00:19:05,192
and not also change your understanding.

208
00:19:05,894 --> 00:19:10,385
So the path is a feedback, it's a loop, it's a sort of feedback loop system.

209
00:19:11,208 --> 00:19:19,228
And you lose nothing by really putting the accent of your spiritual life into right relationship.

210
00:19:19,208 --> 00:19:22,477
which might be a definition for ethics.

211
00:19:23,057 --> 00:19:30,057
Ethics is basically how you relate to human beings, to animals, nature, and so on and so forth.

212
00:19:30,076 --> 00:19:33,285
And by putting the accent on that and seeing how

213
00:19:33,653 --> 00:19:43,269
how we relate to those things, and how we're creating suffering for ourselves, but also situations where other people might suffer.

214
00:19:43,469 --> 00:19:53,204
Remember, we don't cause other people to suffer, but we can definitely create situations where it's very difficult for them not to make the decision that they're going to suffer.

215
00:19:54,026 --> 00:19:59,694
So it's a case of recognizing that we also have a responsibility to...

216
00:20:00,333 --> 00:20:28,904
create situations for other people that they may not make these wrong decisions so by coming back onto that you see you immediately change your attitude and that attitude is one of connection isn't it so another word for connection is love that's all so love is in its most in its most universal sense a sort of a sense of interconnectedness a sense of

217
00:20:29,424 --> 00:20:35,141
of an interconnectedness with the all, as the Buddha would say, which is the all within our consciousness.

218
00:20:37,868 --> 00:20:42,059
And to make that connection as the connection demands.

219
00:20:42,140 --> 00:20:43,063
So sometimes...

220
00:20:43,414 --> 00:20:48,662
As you know, there can be a certain directness, a certain, what's that word?

221
00:20:49,462 --> 00:20:51,005
Aggressive, what's the word?

222
00:20:51,425 --> 00:20:52,126
Not aggressive.

223
00:20:52,768 --> 00:20:53,407
Thank you very much.

224
00:20:53,749 --> 00:20:54,769
Assertiveness.

225
00:20:54,789 --> 00:21:02,079
You can be very assertive and not seem kindly, but it's exactly what was needed in that particular situation.

226
00:21:02,099 --> 00:21:05,845
And other times, of course, you can be very warm-hearted, compassionate, and so on.

227
00:21:06,330 --> 00:21:12,958
So it's a sort of sensitivity that we have to develop towards any situation we're in.

228
00:21:13,659 --> 00:21:23,970
And that means that you've got to launch your attention outwardly into other people around you, into the animals you see, into nature and all that sort of stuff.

229
00:21:24,529 --> 00:21:30,997
And to, as it were, not only take this very isolated position of me in the midst of all this.

230
00:21:32,398 --> 00:21:35,561
So the me has to turn towards a sort of connection which

231
00:21:35,795 --> 00:21:39,279
produces a we, a sort of communion, a community.

232
00:21:40,801 --> 00:21:48,271
So all that, of course, is part and parcel of this growing ethical relationship to the world.

233
00:21:49,393 --> 00:21:56,422
One other way of perhaps talking about ethics is to try and create situations which are to our own benefit.

234
00:21:57,222 --> 00:22:00,347
The Buddha talks about our own benefit, the benefit of somebody else.

235
00:22:00,728 --> 00:22:05,193
You might do something which is not to your particular benefit but to somebody else's benefit.

236
00:22:05,916 --> 00:22:08,440
and to both of myself and to another.

237
00:22:10,241 --> 00:22:16,548
And in that sort of relationship you have that connection, it's always demanding a certain generosity.

238
00:22:17,529 --> 00:22:22,714
And that generosity has that ability to make that connection real, because you're giving.

239
00:22:22,994 --> 00:22:27,359
You're giving something of yourself, whether your wealth or your time for the benefit of others.

240
00:22:28,280 --> 00:22:30,202
And at times you're giving it to yourself.

241
00:22:31,484 --> 00:22:33,747
Sometimes you deserve a biscuit.

242
00:22:35,042 --> 00:22:38,868
Very rare, of course, but occasionally you might say, well, I deserve a biscuit.

243
00:22:40,151 --> 00:22:45,078
So it's a case of recognizing that ethics is beginning to change our attitude.

244
00:22:45,640 --> 00:22:57,598
And as you move outward towards people, move outwards towards nature and animals and all that sort of stuff, of course, you find the opposite, that they're coming towards you.

245
00:22:57,659 --> 00:22:58,681
That's the point.

246
00:22:58,701 --> 00:22:59,582
They're coming towards you.

247
00:22:59,865 --> 00:23:04,010
And that's where the interconnectedness, shall we say, becomes more real for us.

248
00:23:04,050 --> 00:23:09,096
Because we realise that the whole thing is some sort of theatre piece.

249
00:23:09,116 --> 00:23:10,859
It's a sort of play that we're in.

250
00:23:11,440 --> 00:23:13,623
A serious one.

251
00:23:13,863 --> 00:23:21,873
If you want to take a Hindu image of it, a dance, or a Mahayana one, Indra's net.

252
00:23:22,314 --> 00:23:27,240
Everything is interconnected and those interconnections are holographic.

253
00:23:27,359 --> 00:23:28,961
They contain everything else.

254
00:23:29,313 --> 00:23:30,875
within themselves as potential.

255
00:23:32,438 --> 00:23:46,840
So our behaviour in ordinary daily life, the way we act in ordinary daily life, is this constant effort to see the situation more fully, not just myself isolated as an individual.

256
00:23:47,402 --> 00:23:51,528
I remember that's very much a Western thing, this individuality business.

257
00:23:52,569 --> 00:23:55,454
I do my own thing in my own way in my own time, to hell with you lot.

258
00:23:57,393 --> 00:24:07,048
And that sort of individuality causes us to disconnect with people, tremendous loneliness, and with it, of course, anxiety.

259
00:24:08,471 --> 00:24:20,109
And somehow we have to reverse that process and begin to make these connections to create a sense of community, even if the people whom you're with have no sense of community at all, right?

260
00:24:21,794 --> 00:24:28,182
So you're catching the whole situation where everybody's these individual little pods looking after themselves.

261
00:24:28,863 --> 00:24:40,178
And we've somehow got to make that connection with them and to see that they are undermining potential by only turning in towards themselves, only what I want.

262
00:24:41,940 --> 00:24:44,763
And that by opening up to that,

263
00:24:45,048 --> 00:24:55,539
your relationship changes somewhat, and it opens up for them the possibility of changing their relationship.

264
00:24:55,559 --> 00:25:01,787
On a negative side, who's the Russian-American author?

265
00:25:03,028 --> 00:25:05,811
Atlas, what was it, Atlas?

266
00:25:05,832 --> 00:25:06,271
Shrugged.

267
00:25:08,355 --> 00:25:08,654
Shrugged.

268
00:25:08,914 --> 00:25:11,258
So the arch, I mean, it's funny that she was Russian.

269
00:25:11,592 --> 00:25:18,519
coming from presumably a communist background, this sort of arch-individualist, where it's up to you.

270
00:25:18,740 --> 00:25:21,423
You're the one that has to make the world.

271
00:25:21,703 --> 00:25:25,848
You're the one who makes decisions, and the world you live in is completely manufactured by you.

272
00:25:25,868 --> 00:25:26,490
You did it.

273
00:25:27,250 --> 00:25:35,921
And so all these people in Silicon Valley, one or two of them anyway, believe that the billions they've got is all because of me.

274
00:25:36,301 --> 00:25:36,721
I did it.

275
00:25:37,089 --> 00:25:39,801
You know, without me, this would never have happened.

276
00:25:40,183 --> 00:25:44,383
Now, in a sense, of course, there is a touch of truth in that.

277
00:25:44,768 --> 00:25:46,609
They probably instigated it.

278
00:25:46,630 --> 00:25:50,193
They probably had the first idea, like Jobs.

279
00:25:50,473 --> 00:25:52,557
What was his first name?

280
00:25:52,576 --> 00:25:52,856
Steve.

281
00:25:53,037 --> 00:25:53,597
Steve Jobs.

282
00:25:54,038 --> 00:25:58,242
I mean, you know, really a man of, you know, he had these wonderful little ideas.

283
00:25:58,644 --> 00:26:09,935
But to say that all these billions came because of me, you know, to hell with the workforce, to hell with everybody else who's putting their little chips, is just an insanity.

284
00:26:10,596 --> 00:26:13,240
I mean, it's just, you're so isolated, they should put you away.

285
00:26:15,126 --> 00:26:21,317
So it's a case of recognizing that the West especially got itself into this corner.

286
00:26:21,978 --> 00:26:24,122
See, the Eastern people don't think like that.

287
00:26:24,142 --> 00:26:32,055
I saw a program on China, and there was a young woman there saying that she felt that they thought differently.

288
00:26:32,095 --> 00:26:35,380
They thought more in terms of community.

289
00:26:36,118 --> 00:26:49,781
That sort of bringing in other people in some sort of connection where you don't see yourself as forging ahead, the lone pioneer, creating the world just for yourself.

290
00:26:50,804 --> 00:26:55,511
And that's very much, of course, the Buddha's own way of looking at things.

291
00:26:57,162 --> 00:27:00,147
So here we have somebody who has this tremendous insight.

292
00:27:00,709 --> 00:27:05,779
And for one moment, as you know, those of you who know the story, he doubts whether anybody would understand it.

293
00:27:05,819 --> 00:27:09,788
He discovers something which is so extraordinary.

294
00:27:10,469 --> 00:27:13,315
And there's nothing like it being taught anywhere else, remember.

295
00:27:13,750 --> 00:27:16,594
and he doesn't think people would really grasp it.

296
00:27:17,154 --> 00:27:25,886
And he says, it would be just an annoyance to me to try and do it, constantly trying to make people understand this sort of stuff.

297
00:27:25,926 --> 00:27:32,576
But then, in the myth, this great god appears and tells him that there are some with only a little bit of dust in their eyes, and so off he goes.

298
00:27:33,317 --> 00:27:37,462
And there's a lovely little telling tale of how he learns how to be a teacher.

299
00:27:37,784 --> 00:27:41,328
So remember, the insight doesn't make you a genius.

300
00:27:41,368 --> 00:27:42,390
It doesn't make you a teacher.

301
00:27:42,410 --> 00:27:43,571
It doesn't make you anything else.

302
00:27:43,551 --> 00:27:53,583
So on the way back, on his way to see these old companions of his, that's his first thought, he'd go back to these companions that he'd struggled with.

303
00:27:53,603 --> 00:28:08,579
He meets this another ascetic, his name doesn't come to mind, and the ascetic sees him and he sees the charisma, he sees perhaps the glow that's coming from him in terms of this enlightenment that he's just experienced.

304
00:28:08,999 --> 00:28:11,201
And he says to him, he says, you're amazing.

305
00:28:11,221 --> 00:28:12,144
Who is your teacher?

306
00:28:12,183 --> 00:28:15,229
Who is, you know, how did you attain this?

307
00:28:15,568 --> 00:28:17,732
And he says, I am my own teacher.

308
00:28:17,752 --> 00:28:19,075
You know, I am the savior of the world.

309
00:28:19,154 --> 00:28:20,517
I am the fully liberated one.

310
00:28:20,877 --> 00:28:22,319
And the guy says, all right, okay.

311
00:28:22,339 --> 00:28:23,981
And clicks his head and off he goes.

312
00:28:25,243 --> 00:28:28,829
So he must have learned pretty quick that's not quite how you get the message across.

313
00:28:30,143 --> 00:28:39,275
And when he actually meets his old companions, it's completely different because there he sees that he goes back to an old relationship, a friendship with them.

314
00:28:39,634 --> 00:28:42,318
And there's a whole process of discussing.

315
00:28:42,699 --> 00:28:55,154
And while he's discussing with them what he's discovered, which are slowly being formalized in his mind, he constantly asks the questions, have you ever heard me speak like this?

316
00:28:55,574 --> 00:28:59,679
So as he's talking to them, he interrupts himself and he says, have you ever heard me speak like this?

317
00:28:59,719 --> 00:29:01,421
Have you ever heard me say anything like this?

318
00:29:01,902 --> 00:29:13,175
And just very slowly, they're sort of attracted to his teachings and actually all become fully liberated in these wonderful stories.

319
00:29:14,317 --> 00:29:22,527
So this whole business of relationship goes right back, in terms of the Buddha's teaching, right back to him.

320
00:29:22,928 --> 00:29:28,253
And that he didn't just sit there with a sign saying, do not disturb, I'm fully liberated.

321
00:29:28,855 --> 00:29:31,117
But actually he got up and walked.

322
00:29:31,357 --> 00:29:39,768
So from Bodh Gaya to where he found his people over in Sarnath, which is in Varanasi, just north of Varanasi.

323
00:29:40,568 --> 00:29:44,153
I can't remember, it's a few miles, about 300 or 400 miles.

324
00:29:44,253 --> 00:29:46,256
India's a big place, you know.

325
00:29:46,276 --> 00:29:51,923
So it wasn't as though he thought I'd just nip down to Dublin and have a little chat with my old mates.

326
00:29:52,222 --> 00:29:52,884
You've got to walk.

327
00:29:55,010 --> 00:30:01,930
So here we have this teaching about Sila, about...

328
00:30:03,377 --> 00:30:04,638
morality.

329
00:30:05,240 --> 00:30:11,448
And what we're saying is that if we keep our attention on that, this is something we can actually do.

330
00:30:12,268 --> 00:30:15,071
You can't make a decision to have an insight.

331
00:30:15,251 --> 00:30:20,038
You can't say, well, look, I'm going to sit down now and I'm going to have a great insight and liberate myself.

332
00:30:20,117 --> 00:30:21,278
It just doesn't work.

333
00:30:21,318 --> 00:30:23,862
It doesn't work like that.

334
00:30:23,882 --> 00:30:26,424
So we can't make ourselves have an insight.

335
00:30:26,644 --> 00:30:29,689
Insights come when the conditions are ripe.

336
00:30:29,939 --> 00:30:41,286
But what we can do is really correct our behavior and become much more aware of how the delusion is manifesting, the essential delusion to do with the self.

337
00:30:41,306 --> 00:30:44,673
And that's pretty easy for us to perceive.

338
00:30:44,991 --> 00:31:04,653
And through the meditation, if we can maintain a certain level of awareness in daily life, so don't find ourselves rushing and all that sort of stuff, but try to maintain a certain calmness, then we should slowly change these habits.

339
00:31:05,073 --> 00:31:16,347
slowly allow habits that we see as unhealthy to die away, and to build up the good ones through these practices of metta, through goodwill practices, and through having right attitude.

340
00:31:18,089 --> 00:31:19,893
So, for instance, work, you see.

341
00:31:20,113 --> 00:31:22,276
It may be that work's hard at this time.

342
00:31:22,316 --> 00:31:24,018
It may be that it's meaningless to you.

343
00:31:25,059 --> 00:31:29,125
It doesn't have any particular meaningfulness to you.

344
00:31:29,346 --> 00:31:32,650
You just ended up doing this work because that's what was on offer.

345
00:31:32,967 --> 00:31:35,809
It just brings on the bacon.

346
00:31:35,829 --> 00:31:39,173
But you can change your attitude completely and see it as one of service.

347
00:31:39,492 --> 00:31:42,876
And then you immediately connect with whomever you're servicing.

348
00:31:43,758 --> 00:31:49,803
There was an example of somebody who was on the coins on these motorways, tolls.

349
00:31:51,085 --> 00:31:58,892
And the way she made it meaningful to herself was to greet people when they came meaningfully.

350
00:31:59,153 --> 00:31:59,633
You know, like,

351
00:32:00,523 --> 00:32:01,305
What a great day.

352
00:32:01,545 --> 00:32:02,125
How are you?

353
00:32:02,226 --> 00:32:04,970
Well, that's a sort of connection there.

354
00:32:05,049 --> 00:32:07,473
It wasn't just, you know, stick the money in there.

355
00:32:09,056 --> 00:32:12,039
Looking really glum inside this little box.

356
00:32:13,722 --> 00:32:17,788
So she found meaningfulness from it, from just that simple connection.

357
00:32:18,429 --> 00:32:22,154
And that, of course, lifts your heart.

358
00:32:22,174 --> 00:32:26,240
So there's all sorts of little parts of our lives.

359
00:32:26,300 --> 00:32:27,982
If you...

360
00:32:28,553 --> 00:32:35,053
Keep a diary or keep some sort of log of in the morning, you see.

361
00:32:35,894 --> 00:32:37,179
Who are the first people you meet?

362
00:32:37,440 --> 00:32:39,204
Have you prepared yourself to meet them?

363
00:32:39,843 --> 00:32:49,696
So the matter in the morning, you see, if you're going to work and there's people whom you're upset with, you see, if you direct your goodwill towards them, it does change your behavior to them.

364
00:32:50,137 --> 00:33:00,432
And when they see that you're not angry, you're not about to get your revenge, it opens up a little avenue for them to reestablish a working relationship.

365
00:33:00,987 --> 00:33:03,349
Not always, but at least one can try.

366
00:33:04,750 --> 00:33:10,718
So there's a whole process there of ethical behavior which we can actually get hold of.

367
00:33:10,778 --> 00:33:12,720
We can actually do something about.

368
00:33:17,765 --> 00:33:25,753
But then when we go deeper into that, into ethical behavior, then of course we come across this business of a self.

369
00:33:25,773 --> 00:33:29,678
And really that's where the, shall we say, where

370
00:33:30,063 --> 00:33:31,865
the trouble really lies.

371
00:33:34,270 --> 00:33:46,133
So when the Buddha talks about delusion, he talks about these three things, greed, aversion and delusion, or acquisitiveness, aversion, which also includes fear, and delusion.

372
00:33:47,455 --> 00:33:50,821
This delusion is really one of identity.

373
00:33:52,237 --> 00:34:01,048
And so the meditation is trying to undermine this wrong identity we have by making everything into an object for ourselves.

374
00:34:01,930 --> 00:34:14,346
So that's the importance of really noting, really creating that space between the knowing or the knower, at this point the knower, the feeler, the one who knows,

375
00:34:14,561 --> 00:34:27,342
and really holding that point within ourselves where we are actually not so much sometimes aware of what's happening, but the distance between the knower and what's happening.

376
00:34:27,362 --> 00:34:36,177
So for instance, now looking at me, you can be aware just of me, but you can also become aware of the space that is between us.

377
00:34:36,197 --> 00:34:40,384
So it's becoming aware of the mental space that lies between the knower

378
00:34:40,702 --> 00:34:45,590
the feeler, the one who is experiencing things, and the actual experience that's being had.

379
00:34:46,431 --> 00:34:53,882
By doing that, we're actually unwittingly disidentifying with it completely, because it's not me.

380
00:34:56,447 --> 00:35:00,894
And the noting can be of great help there, because you're actually pointing to it.

381
00:35:00,914 --> 00:35:05,282
Say, there's pain, there's an emotional state, there's an image in the mind.

382
00:35:05,802 --> 00:35:07,164
Thought's a bit more difficult, but...

383
00:35:08,932 --> 00:35:15,864
So that process of disidentifying, all we're doing is relocating our identity.

384
00:35:16,827 --> 00:35:19,471
So the basic identity would be physical.

385
00:35:20,311 --> 00:35:28,666
So when we eat something and we just get lost in that beautiful taste, or when we trap our finger in the door, there's just that one moment where we are the body.

386
00:35:29,748 --> 00:35:31,751
Me and the pain, there's no separation.

387
00:35:32,137 --> 00:35:35,561
And then of course you jump out of it, get all angry and kick the door.

388
00:35:36,101 --> 00:35:38,704
So it's a case of recognizing that there is a body self.

389
00:35:39,085 --> 00:35:48,978
So what we mean by identity is a loss of self-awareness into becoming what it is we're experiencing.

390
00:35:48,998 --> 00:35:51,782
Another example would be watching a DVD.

391
00:35:52,150 --> 00:36:00,485
So you can watch a DVD from the point of view of just an interest in the acting or the directing, in which case it always remains something objective you're looking at.

392
00:36:01,106 --> 00:36:06,295
But you can also just fall into it as an enjoyment.

393
00:36:06,527 --> 00:36:11,054
And you just get lost in the mystery or the criminality or whatever it is.

394
00:36:11,474 --> 00:36:14,079
And you lose the sense of me watching the film.

395
00:36:14,559 --> 00:36:16,523
Me and watching the film become one.

396
00:36:16,543 --> 00:36:22,771
So at that point, you're identifying with all the mentation that's going on created by this film.

397
00:36:23,833 --> 00:36:25,094
So you become the mind, right?

398
00:36:25,114 --> 00:36:27,038
You become the heart, become your emotions.

399
00:36:28,018 --> 00:36:33,226
So that's what we mean by identity, right?

400
00:36:33,746 --> 00:36:44,503
So long as there's a sense of self observing something, feeling something, then it's a connection of possession.

401
00:36:46,527 --> 00:36:54,237
In other words, what I'm looking at is not me, but is owned by me.

402
00:36:54,858 --> 00:36:56,121
So I'm talking internally.

403
00:36:56,442 --> 00:36:57,804
I'm talking about pain in the knee.

404
00:36:58,344 --> 00:36:59,666
So it'd be my knee.

405
00:37:00,427 --> 00:37:00,547
Right?

406
00:37:00,882 --> 00:37:11,231
Even though I say I feel anxious, the fact that I'm aware of it means that it can't be me, but somehow I own it.

407
00:37:11,411 --> 00:37:15,275
Somehow I'm identifying with it as a point of ownership.

408
00:37:16,195 --> 00:37:28,266
Now, ownership, of course, brings a lot of pain with it, as you know, because even of things that you own, if somebody nips off with your mobile or something like that, I mean, it's a horror, isn't it?

409
00:37:28,286 --> 00:37:30,248
It's weeping and gnashing of teeth, anger.

410
00:37:31,409 --> 00:37:32,130
Call the police.

411
00:37:32,731 --> 00:37:39,485
I mean, anything arises negatively because somebody's thieved your phone.

412
00:37:40,126 --> 00:37:40,646
For heaven's sake.

413
00:37:42,351 --> 00:37:43,413
So we don't know.

414
00:37:43,432 --> 00:37:48,362
We don't know the suffering behind possession until we lose what it is we possess.

415
00:37:49,465 --> 00:37:50,666
That's pretty straightforward.

416
00:37:51,202 --> 00:38:01,554
And when we actually look at it rationally, the only thing you can do with a thing, like a phone or a TV or a car or whatever, is use it.

417
00:38:02,255 --> 00:38:03,635
You can only use things, right?

418
00:38:03,876 --> 00:38:06,458
To own it is a fiction, isn't it?

419
00:38:06,500 --> 00:38:10,943
It's a legal fiction, which works so long until the thief takes it.

420
00:38:10,963 --> 00:38:11,545
And then it's his.

421
00:38:12,286 --> 00:38:14,929
It's no good you going around saying, he's got my phone.

422
00:38:15,009 --> 00:38:17,331
It's his phone.

423
00:38:17,612 --> 00:38:19,893
I like to make the point of that because it was an occasion.

424
00:38:20,228 --> 00:38:28,639
in the Sangha, that's the Buddhist order in Sri Lanka, where a thief came and stole this monk's little watch.

425
00:38:28,659 --> 00:38:31,724
That's what I remember it as, this little clock.

426
00:38:33,025 --> 00:38:37,211
And he ran after the thief and got it back.

427
00:38:38,373 --> 00:38:40,938
And he was accused by Sangha members of thieving.

428
00:38:44,302 --> 00:38:46,184
And he actually had to leave the order.

429
00:38:46,333 --> 00:38:48,157
The sangha, yes, yeah.

430
00:38:48,177 --> 00:38:50,501
It's because it's no longer his and he took it back.

431
00:38:52,903 --> 00:38:55,327
Which is really strange to anybody else in the world.

432
00:38:56,009 --> 00:38:57,711
But that's basically it.

433
00:38:59,675 --> 00:39:01,217
Strange, yeah?

434
00:39:01,237 --> 00:39:04,922
So it makes you think about ownership.

435
00:39:08,628 --> 00:39:13,556
So we've got this relationship of identity with something.

436
00:39:13,942 --> 00:39:23,599
And remember that happiness, real happiness in the sense of an absolute happiness, is when we fall into the emotion of happiness.

437
00:39:23,679 --> 00:39:24,922
We become the happiness.

438
00:39:25,923 --> 00:39:36,202
When you watch an uproarious film and you're just laughing your head off, great guffaws and all that, you, the guffaw in the film, become one and the same thing.

439
00:39:36,436 --> 00:39:46,150
When a comic comes on and you're laughing your head off, you, the comic, you lose that sense of me watching television.

440
00:39:46,170 --> 00:39:47,851
You're just there within the laughter.

441
00:39:49,514 --> 00:40:00,570
And that's one reason why you get people doing these dangerous sports, because in a dangerous sport, you've got to give your whole attention and you lose yourself in the sport.

442
00:40:00,989 --> 00:40:11,601
you know, canoeing down rapids and stuff like that, which are dangerous in themselves, which mean that there has to be a heightened sense of awareness, a heightened sense of awareness.

443
00:40:11,621 --> 00:40:16,626
You've got to be right there with the moment, and there's a sheer joy of the adrenaline coming up.

444
00:40:17,288 --> 00:40:23,014
And you lose yourself into it, and it becomes like an addiction to try and get back into the zone.

445
00:40:25,458 --> 00:40:31,583
These moments of happiness, when we're completely happy, paradoxically is when we don't know it.

446
00:40:32,626 --> 00:40:35,288
As soon as you come out of that happy state, you've lost it.

447
00:40:35,949 --> 00:40:42,335
There may still be a feeling of happiness, but actually there's something in you which knows that the happiness is on the way out.

448
00:40:43,237 --> 00:40:43,577
It's gone.

449
00:40:44,438 --> 00:40:47,742
So it's one of these little paradoxes about identity.

450
00:40:48,581 --> 00:40:52,967
And it's the same, of course, on the negative side, when you identify with a hellish state with something.

451
00:40:53,369 --> 00:40:54,650
just for that one moment.

452
00:40:54,731 --> 00:40:55,471
That's what you are.

453
00:40:58,934 --> 00:41:08,505
So, we have to take a little step even further back there to find out where this sense of identity originates.

454
00:41:10,168 --> 00:41:20,079
So, in our meditation, when we sit there observing, feeling, things like that, we've accessed this observation post.

455
00:41:20,099 --> 00:41:22,902
There's a lovely phrase that comes from Nyanaponika, his book,

456
00:41:23,255 --> 00:41:26,458
The Heart of Buddhist Meditation is still a classic, really worth reading.

457
00:41:27,460 --> 00:41:42,822
And there's some body up here somewhere, somewhere a couple of, I don't know, centimeters or so behind this point here, which is looking, feeling, and knowing everything from this sort of place.

458
00:41:44,945 --> 00:41:50,713
And from that place, we've detached from the body.

459
00:41:50,929 --> 00:41:51,871
It's no longer us.

460
00:41:52,210 --> 00:41:53,112
There's the body.

461
00:41:53,152 --> 00:41:58,177
That's why we use these noting words and we don't put the sense of I feel something.

462
00:41:58,197 --> 00:41:59,739
There's just the feeling.

463
00:42:00,219 --> 00:42:02,041
So we're trying to make it quite objective.

464
00:42:02,541 --> 00:42:05,523
Same with emotions, same with images that come to the mind.

465
00:42:06,985 --> 00:42:19,197
So that sort of disengagement, that sort of pulling ourselves, pulling this awareness out of its confusion with this psychophysical organism.

466
00:42:20,005 --> 00:42:21,306
Just be able to see it.

467
00:42:22,809 --> 00:42:31,704
And it finds itself as being this very objective observer, objective feeler, objective experiencer.

468
00:42:31,724 --> 00:42:35,170
But of course, it can't be that either, can it?

469
00:42:35,190 --> 00:42:37,072
It can't be what it's aware of.

470
00:42:37,594 --> 00:42:39,297
The perceiver can't be the perceived.

471
00:42:40,777 --> 00:42:50,769
So this sense of I am looking, I am feeling, that sense of self there, right there, that can't be you either.

472
00:42:52,773 --> 00:42:53,273
Is that correct?

473
00:42:54,315 --> 00:42:55,195
Not vigorously, please.

474
00:42:58,039 --> 00:43:03,545
See, so there's something that is aware of itself.

475
00:43:05,855 --> 00:43:08,539
There's something that is aware of itself.

476
00:43:08,938 --> 00:43:13,965
Now, the only time that we experience that, so we say physically, is when you look in the mirror.

477
00:43:13,985 --> 00:43:16,590
So when you look in the mirror, you're aware that this is your face.

478
00:43:18,853 --> 00:43:19,934
But you know it's not your face.

479
00:43:20,835 --> 00:43:22,797
It's actually just a mirror image of your face.

480
00:43:22,838 --> 00:43:24,239
And of course, it's the wrong way around, isn't it?

481
00:43:25,402 --> 00:43:26,422
It's not how people see you.

482
00:43:28,525 --> 00:43:29,907
You've all done the two mirror trick.

483
00:43:29,927 --> 00:43:31,570
I always ask that.

484
00:43:31,851 --> 00:43:33,293
Who hasn't done the two mirror trick?

485
00:43:34,233 --> 00:43:34,914
Fancy.

486
00:43:34,934 --> 00:43:35,675
Oh, you haven't lived.

487
00:43:36,567 --> 00:43:38,188
You've got to do the two-mirror trick.

488
00:43:38,429 --> 00:43:42,873
So you've got to look into a mirror, and you've got to take a second mirror that looks into the mirror.

489
00:43:43,532 --> 00:43:47,797
And you've got to catch your face in this mirror, because it's turned around again.

490
00:43:47,817 --> 00:43:50,179
Well, it's a horror thing, isn't it?

491
00:43:50,259 --> 00:43:52,161
It's like listening to your own voice for the first time.

492
00:43:52,802 --> 00:43:54,083
Or worse, seeing yourself in a video.

493
00:43:55,324 --> 00:43:59,547
So there's something about that sense of self.

494
00:43:59,628 --> 00:44:02,650
Now, I came across this.

495
00:44:02,731 --> 00:44:05,172
I remembered this myth of narcissism.

496
00:44:07,110 --> 00:44:13,099
And in Greek psychology, of course, it's about a wrong self-love, a sort of pride, I think.

497
00:44:13,858 --> 00:44:19,146
And he looks into the pool and falls in love with himself, as you might say.

498
00:44:19,746 --> 00:44:22,690
And, of course, he goes to embrace it and falls into the water.

499
00:44:22,951 --> 00:44:27,556
Water is always, remember, an image of creation in mythology.

500
00:44:28,297 --> 00:44:31,802
So here we have, from a Greek point of view, somebody who,

501
00:44:32,085 --> 00:44:35,471
who falls in love with themselves through a sense of pride and whatnot.

502
00:44:35,490 --> 00:44:41,438
But it works brilliantly as an image for our essential delusion.

503
00:44:41,458 --> 00:44:46,146
And the important thing to grasp is that we actually fall in love.

504
00:44:47,208 --> 00:44:48,909
We're actually in love with ourselves.

505
00:44:49,771 --> 00:44:51,072
That's the basic platform.

506
00:44:51,813 --> 00:45:01,550
We wake up, I know sometimes, well, sometimes you wake in the morning and you say, you know, here I am again, you know, and sometimes you wake up and you say, oh, not you again.

507
00:45:03,152 --> 00:45:11,527
But prior to that, prior to that, you see, there must be a moment where this awareness becomes aware of itself.

508
00:45:12,088 --> 00:45:13,369
But it can never see itself.

509
00:45:13,530 --> 00:45:14,893
The eye cannot see itself.

510
00:45:16,275 --> 00:45:17,516
The nose can't smell itself.

511
00:45:18,661 --> 00:45:29,050
If the nose had a constant odor of, say, I don't know, curry, how could you, everything else would be ruined by it.

512
00:45:29,291 --> 00:45:34,255
So the sense bases are completely clean of exactly what it is that they are aware of, that they sense.

513
00:45:35,076 --> 00:45:39,599
So this awareness, you see, can never know itself as an object.

514
00:45:39,619 --> 00:45:43,724
And therefore that sense of self-awareness must be a delusion.

515
00:45:46,626 --> 00:45:48,447
So the mirror image.

516
00:45:48,715 --> 00:45:57,226
So now, what technique, what can we do to undermine that very deep delusion?

517
00:45:57,286 --> 00:45:59,550
Because that's our primary object.

518
00:46:00,690 --> 00:46:07,940
The primary object we make is this awareness coming into the mind and catching its own image.

519
00:46:08,621 --> 00:46:11,425
How do we experience that image of the self?

520
00:46:11,987 --> 00:46:14,110
It's a presence, isn't it?

521
00:46:14,130 --> 00:46:15,110
It's a sense of presence.

522
00:46:17,588 --> 00:46:20,672
Whenever you're awake, there's always you.

523
00:46:23,775 --> 00:46:25,097
There's always a sense of presence.

524
00:46:25,936 --> 00:46:32,925
Now that sense of presence is a feeling image of the awareness in the mind.

525
00:46:34,047 --> 00:46:44,318
So it's as though that now has to become the object to observe and to really see whether in fact it's permanent or not.

526
00:46:45,318 --> 00:46:47,561
Now in Buddhist psychology, there are

527
00:46:48,014 --> 00:46:53,159
in the human being, the Buddha talks about these five aggregates.

528
00:46:54,260 --> 00:46:55,342
So the first one is the body.

529
00:46:55,842 --> 00:46:59,286
But it's not the physical body that you might think of.

530
00:46:59,306 --> 00:47:01,809
It's often translated as that, just our physicality.

531
00:47:02,170 --> 00:47:06,414
But you have to ask yourself, what is it you actually know of your body?

532
00:47:09,557 --> 00:47:12,481
Do you know what your liver is doing?

533
00:47:12,501 --> 00:47:13,481
Now, see?

534
00:47:14,623 --> 00:47:16,806
Have you any idea what's happening in your brain

535
00:47:17,865 --> 00:47:20,630
Did you know it was mostly fatty substance?

536
00:47:20,650 --> 00:47:21,610
That's what they tell me anyway.

537
00:47:22,050 --> 00:47:25,416
Did you know that your body has 10 trillion individual cells?

538
00:47:26,737 --> 00:47:29,681
And they're all screaming for whatever.

539
00:47:31,123 --> 00:47:36,148
And you also host 100 trillion guest cells, which are helping you do things like digest.

540
00:47:39,753 --> 00:47:43,338
Did you know that the cornea of your eye changes once every week?

541
00:47:44,840 --> 00:47:47,704
Every week, you can look at the mirror and say, you weren't here last week.

542
00:47:49,405 --> 00:47:52,768
And they tell you that every atom in your body has changed every seven years.

543
00:47:53,509 --> 00:47:54,869
This is what they say.

544
00:47:54,889 --> 00:47:57,032
So it's not as though we know the body.

545
00:47:57,371 --> 00:47:59,793
The body has its own little life form.

546
00:47:59,813 --> 00:48:00,375
Who knows what?

547
00:48:01,094 --> 00:48:03,277
What we can know is how we experience the body.

548
00:48:04,157 --> 00:48:11,123
And that's where this business of pain, pleasure, and all that sort of stuff comes in.

549
00:48:11,143 --> 00:48:13,666
So that's the first aggregate, is how we experience the body.

550
00:48:13,985 --> 00:48:15,887
And the basic experience of the body is the breath.

551
00:48:17,548 --> 00:48:19,311
It starts with the breath, and then

552
00:48:19,543 --> 00:48:26,253
we have what's known as the four elements, the four great elements, which is fire, earth, water, and air.

553
00:48:26,713 --> 00:48:37,668
And these refer to temperature, pressure, elasticity, connectivity, can't think of the word, and movement.

554
00:48:38,349 --> 00:48:41,333
So whenever you drop down below pain,

555
00:48:41,717 --> 00:48:47,884
the image of pain, and you go into the pain, then you're at the level of the body itself.

556
00:48:48,405 --> 00:48:51,659
Not the body itself, but how the mind experiences the body.

557
00:48:53,007 --> 00:48:57,652
That's your first heap, just an aggregate of sensations and feelings.

558
00:48:58,353 --> 00:49:03,519
And then the next one is feelings.

559
00:49:03,539 --> 00:49:07,405
Feelings are physical and mental feelings.

560
00:49:07,885 --> 00:49:10,309
Not to be confused with mental states.

561
00:49:10,568 --> 00:49:13,032
They're what mental states create in the body as a feeling.

562
00:49:13,333 --> 00:49:18,199
So when you feel heavy because you're a bit depressed, that's the Vedan, that's the feeling.

563
00:49:18,219 --> 00:49:21,342
And according to the Buddha, all these feelings are feelings.

564
00:49:21,695 --> 00:49:32,065
There's no need to differentiate them apart from the fact that some of them are coming from the body into the mind and some coming from the mind-heart into the body.

565
00:49:32,985 --> 00:49:34,367
So that is the connection there.

566
00:49:34,387 --> 00:49:35,969
Then there's perceptions.

567
00:49:35,989 --> 00:49:39,452
So these are, remember, your photocopies that you make.

568
00:49:39,472 --> 00:49:43,936
And these grow into concepts, concrete concepts, even abstract concepts.

569
00:49:45,057 --> 00:49:50,722
And what they do is they make you look at the world in a certain way.

570
00:49:52,119 --> 00:49:54,123
And then the third one are your sankaras.

571
00:49:54,143 --> 00:49:55,465
So these are your mental states.

572
00:49:56,128 --> 00:50:05,826
These are what we're referring to when we talk about our habits, the way that we can become happy, the way we become sad, and so on and so forth.

573
00:50:06,085 --> 00:50:07,789
The mental states that we're in.

574
00:50:07,809 --> 00:50:09,052
And finally, consciousness.

575
00:50:09,472 --> 00:50:12,599
Now, the problem is translation.

576
00:50:12,898 --> 00:50:14,382
And the Buddha himself...

577
00:50:14,614 --> 00:50:20,181
has problems trying to find the right word to express what he wants to express.

578
00:50:20,201 --> 00:50:22,724
And the words change depending on the situation.

579
00:50:23,565 --> 00:50:26,748
So in the Pali there's two major words.

580
00:50:26,809 --> 00:50:28,210
There's citta and vijnana.

581
00:50:28,510 --> 00:50:32,496
Citta refers to what we would normally have called in the old days the soul.

582
00:50:33,257 --> 00:50:40,605
Not the everlasting spirit, but the soul meaning this combination of heart and mind, which we split.

583
00:50:40,804 --> 00:50:45,811
In our age of enlightenment we took rationality and feeling away from each other.

584
00:50:45,831 --> 00:50:49,295
So bringing them together as one composite.

585
00:50:49,335 --> 00:50:51,856
So what you think you feel and what you feel you think.

586
00:50:53,139 --> 00:50:58,003
And if you look at every time you think of something you'll see the heart's in there somewhere.

587
00:50:58,764 --> 00:51:01,829
And when the heart moves you'll see there's a thought related to it.

588
00:51:01,849 --> 00:51:03,530
So it's not as though they're completely separate.

589
00:51:04,291 --> 00:51:05,512
They're working one off the other.

590
00:51:06,753 --> 00:51:09,376
But they're obviously two different modes.

591
00:51:11,467 --> 00:51:18,559
And all these things have to be held somewhere.

592
00:51:18,579 --> 00:51:20,961
They have to be held somewhere to be known.

593
00:51:21,943 --> 00:51:23,726
So that which knows is awareness.

594
00:51:24,969 --> 00:51:28,894
But something has to hold it long enough for it to be known.

595
00:51:29,195 --> 00:51:29,976
And that's the screen.

596
00:51:30,117 --> 00:51:31,800
That's the screen of consciousness.

597
00:51:32,782 --> 00:51:36,748
So when we talk about consciousness, we're not talking about...

598
00:51:38,315 --> 00:51:42,621
We're not talking about the process of that, the process of reasoning.

599
00:51:43,181 --> 00:51:46,648
We're not talking about the process of emotions and moods.

600
00:51:47,148 --> 00:51:50,213
We're not talking about the process of perceiving.

601
00:51:51,114 --> 00:52:01,150
We're talking about some sort of multidimensional screen that just for a moment holds the totality of that moment.

602
00:52:01,855 --> 00:52:11,275
for us as we experience it through this psychophysical organism so if I stub my toe on the screen there just comes pain

603
00:52:11,541 --> 00:52:12,844
Right.

604
00:52:12,864 --> 00:52:13,425
That's the first.

605
00:52:13,664 --> 00:52:14,746
And then that disappears.

606
00:52:15,387 --> 00:52:18,413
And then the reason why I stubbed my toe.

607
00:52:19,034 --> 00:52:19,514
Right.

608
00:52:19,534 --> 00:52:26,786
So I'm getting this chopped up momentary screenings of what's happening in the present moment.

609
00:52:26,806 --> 00:52:32,335
And so fast is this screening that it's all joined together into a continuum.

610
00:52:32,449 --> 00:52:38,717
And that's where we perceive some sort of continuity when it's not there.

611
00:52:39,619 --> 00:52:43,284
And the continuity gives us the impression of everlastingness.

612
00:52:44,005 --> 00:52:48,070
And that gives us the impression that it's always me.

613
00:52:48,090 --> 00:52:48,871
I never change.

614
00:52:49,391 --> 00:52:51,393
All these other things are changing, but not me.

615
00:52:52,074 --> 00:53:00,927
And that's one of the core insights of the Buddha, that the sense of me, the sense of self, is also arising and passing away.

616
00:53:01,947 --> 00:53:02,068
Right?

617
00:53:02,351 --> 00:53:08,159
And that's what he means when he says that there is a self, but it's not a self.

618
00:53:09,360 --> 00:53:16,208
Because in those days, the self would have referred to something that we might refer to now as an everlasting soul or a spirit.

619
00:53:17,869 --> 00:53:27,920
Now, this self that we're talking about is that mirror image, which is being held every so often on that screen, and we get a sense of the feeling of presence there.

620
00:53:29,217 --> 00:53:43,313
So in your meditation, you see, when everything's quite calm and you're watching the breath and et cetera, et cetera, in that calmness, you know, turn towards that sense of presence, right?

621
00:53:43,333 --> 00:53:47,559
And make it an object that you're looking at.

622
00:53:47,579 --> 00:53:47,719
Okay?

623
00:53:48,519 --> 00:53:58,751
And in that way, you know, you're coming to distance away from the mind at that initial level of contact.

624
00:54:00,300 --> 00:54:07,487
And becoming more and more aware that what is aware is not part of that matrix, of the body, heart, mind matrix.

625
00:54:08,548 --> 00:54:10,030
And that's the process of awakening.

626
00:54:11,092 --> 00:54:12,693
The awakening is in the awareness.

627
00:54:14,335 --> 00:54:15,516
Awakening is in the awareness.

628
00:54:16,797 --> 00:54:17,518
It's not in the mind.

629
00:54:19,460 --> 00:54:26,847
And one of the other understandings that we have is actually awareness that's suffering.

630
00:54:29,916 --> 00:54:30,538
That's suffering.

631
00:54:32,320 --> 00:54:32,960
It's suffering.

632
00:54:33,882 --> 00:54:37,125
It's the awareness that is suffering.

633
00:54:37,144 --> 00:54:39,268
Through that wrong identity.

634
00:54:41,951 --> 00:54:43,291
So the body doesn't suffer.

635
00:54:43,373 --> 00:54:44,353
The body just has pain.

636
00:54:45,795 --> 00:54:46,115
Correct?

637
00:54:46,976 --> 00:54:47,898
The heart doesn't suffer.

638
00:54:48,237 --> 00:54:49,480
The heart just has emotions.

639
00:54:49,500 --> 00:54:52,182
You can distance from them.

640
00:54:53,364 --> 00:54:53,543
See?

641
00:54:53,885 --> 00:54:55,445
Thoughts are hardly suffering.

642
00:54:55,467 --> 00:54:56,768
They're usually just flitting little things.

643
00:54:58,452 --> 00:55:03,139
So there's something in us which, through its wrong relationship, is actually causing suffering for itself.

644
00:55:03,661 --> 00:55:05,264
And that's the Buddha within.

645
00:55:05,284 --> 00:55:15,079
That's where the search for the end of happiness, the end of suffering, as well, that's where the search for the end of suffering is coming from.

646
00:55:15,320 --> 00:55:16,302
It's not coming from the body.

647
00:55:16,983 --> 00:55:19,909
It's not coming from our emotional or mental state.

648
00:55:19,969 --> 00:55:24,155
It's coming from this essential nature seeking its own liberation.

649
00:55:26,177 --> 00:55:37,289
So when you actually contemplate that, you can see how subtle it is.

650
00:55:37,309 --> 00:55:38,610
The problem is in the seeing.

651
00:55:41,114 --> 00:55:42,436
It's not in what is being seen.

652
00:55:45,378 --> 00:55:48,882
I'll give you an example of that from when I went to Sri Lanka.

653
00:55:50,083 --> 00:55:54,007
I was standing with one or two monks and there was this barking going on.

654
00:55:54,376 --> 00:55:57,219
And I couldn't work out what his barking was.

655
00:55:57,239 --> 00:55:57,880
And it's monkeys.

656
00:55:58,440 --> 00:55:59,762
I didn't know monkeys barked.

657
00:56:01,344 --> 00:56:05,148
And I said to them, when they said, well, those are monkeys.

658
00:56:05,168 --> 00:56:05,909
I said, where are they?

659
00:56:05,949 --> 00:56:06,789
They said, they're up there.

660
00:56:07,130 --> 00:56:08,532
And they pointed to this tree.

661
00:56:08,972 --> 00:56:12,215
And for the life of me, I couldn't see any monkeys.

662
00:56:12,235 --> 00:56:13,416
I said, I'm looking up there.

663
00:56:13,436 --> 00:56:13,876
I said, where?

664
00:56:13,936 --> 00:56:14,358
I couldn't see.

665
00:56:14,438 --> 00:56:16,539
I said, there's a whole troop of them.

666
00:56:16,820 --> 00:56:18,121
There's about 20, 25 of them up there.

667
00:56:18,625 --> 00:56:20,449
And I'm looking and looking and looking.

668
00:56:20,469 --> 00:56:23,777
And then just suddenly, woof, I can see these monkeys.

669
00:56:23,817 --> 00:56:24,438
They're everywhere.

670
00:56:26,141 --> 00:56:28,025
And it's because my eye wasn't trained to see.

671
00:56:28,065 --> 00:56:29,829
See?

672
00:56:30,311 --> 00:56:34,581
And in that delusion, I would have gone away and said, well, monkeys are ghosts.

673
00:56:34,601 --> 00:56:35,824
Only some people could see them.

674
00:56:37,204 --> 00:56:43,818
There was a case of somebody who was born blind, I read this little article, who was given sight.

675
00:56:44,719 --> 00:56:48,927
And the psychiatrist who was helping him would take him to places.

676
00:56:49,108 --> 00:56:54,637
And the one that he mentioned was a zoo and took him to a cage where there was an ape.

677
00:56:55,880 --> 00:56:57,103
And he couldn't see it.

678
00:56:58,096 --> 00:57:00,038
I mean, an ape in the cage.

679
00:57:00,199 --> 00:57:00,960
You could not see it.

680
00:57:01,320 --> 00:57:05,985
So he took this man to a statue of an ape.

681
00:57:06,606 --> 00:57:09,429
And he felt it with his eyes closed so that he got a mental picture of it.

682
00:57:09,630 --> 00:57:14,797
And when he went back to the cage, he could see the ape.

683
00:57:14,817 --> 00:57:27,192
So our search for liberation from suffering, from our own personal suffering, is the sharpening of this internal seeing.

684
00:57:28,099 --> 00:57:32,646
And the Buddha gives us these cues, he gives us these clues as to which way to approach it.

685
00:57:33,907 --> 00:57:38,532
So it's the impermanence, impermanence, but radical impermanence.

686
00:57:38,552 --> 00:57:42,396
It's not that something is changing, it's that something is arising and passing away.

687
00:57:42,797 --> 00:57:49,445
Now when we say that something is arising and passing away, we're not talking about the physical world as we know it, or as we don't know it.

688
00:57:51,387 --> 00:57:53,291
We're talking about consciousness.

689
00:57:53,992 --> 00:57:55,773
Consciousness arising and passing away.

690
00:57:56,695 --> 00:57:56,775
See?

691
00:57:56,795 --> 00:57:56,875
See?

692
00:57:59,436 --> 00:58:01,139
And consciousness is just a mirror.

693
00:58:01,860 --> 00:58:03,440
But it seems so real to us.

694
00:58:03,481 --> 00:58:04,202
That's the problem.

695
00:58:04,682 --> 00:58:06,925
It seems so real.

696
00:58:06,945 --> 00:58:15,795
And then there's this whole business of relationship that comes up because of this essential delusion of always trying to protect myself.

697
00:58:16,094 --> 00:58:18,257
Remember that our relationship is one of love.

698
00:58:18,838 --> 00:58:21,701
So I'm acquiring things so that I can feel safe.

699
00:58:21,981 --> 00:58:26,726
I feel so much safer if I have a billion in the bank rather than just a few pounds.

700
00:58:27,601 --> 00:58:28,847
And I collect things.

701
00:58:28,907 --> 00:58:30,313
I collect friends.

702
00:58:30,936 --> 00:58:31,822
Makes me feel safe.

703
00:58:31,922 --> 00:58:33,931
I collect objects.

704
00:58:34,300 --> 00:58:37,362
See, that acquisitiveness is really trying to make me feel safe.

705
00:58:38,083 --> 00:58:47,594
Now, when I feel safe, I obviously don't want anybody to disturb me, to disturb my happiness that I've got now from this security.

706
00:58:48,375 --> 00:58:49,635
And so the aversion comes.

707
00:58:49,735 --> 00:58:53,721
Anybody who's going to upset me is an enemy, whatever it is.

708
00:58:54,661 --> 00:58:58,025
And, of course, if the enemy's too big, I've got to run for it.

709
00:58:58,045 --> 00:59:02,670
So there's your three basic attitudes arising out of that delusion.

710
00:59:03,072 --> 00:59:05,315
acquisitiveness, aversion, and fear.

711
00:59:06,056 --> 00:59:20,351
And from then, when we act out of that, by the way we think, by the way we speak, and by the way we act, we're actually creating our ethical creations in this world, and they, of course, have consequences.

712
00:59:20,952 --> 00:59:24,336
They not only have consequences outwardly, but they have consequences inwardly.

713
00:59:25,117 --> 00:59:31,105
So the more you feel fearful, the more you'll hate.

714
00:59:31,371 --> 00:59:33,474
The more you hate, the more you fear your enemy.

715
00:59:33,675 --> 00:59:35,878
I mean, the paranoia is just there within us.

716
00:59:37,219 --> 00:59:40,704
The more you have, the more you're afraid of losing.

717
00:59:42,487 --> 00:59:54,983
So it's really going beyond that and recognizing that when you look at the spiritual traditions, the people whom we honor, really honor, like Jesus Christ, St. Francis of Assisi, they don't have anything.

718
00:59:58,338 --> 01:00:00,159
I mean, I'm a monastic.

719
01:00:00,199 --> 01:00:02,043
I'm not supposed to have anything, but I've got a lot.

720
01:00:05,047 --> 01:00:10,893
I've got my mobile phone for a start, which I'm very afraid of losing.

721
01:00:10,914 --> 01:00:19,346
So you see, this idea of letting go of something is to be manifest in the way that we actually live.

722
01:00:20,567 --> 01:00:24,311
And that brings us back to our ethics.

723
01:00:25,927 --> 01:00:28,351
So we've really been around the houses this evening, my goodness.

724
01:00:28,853 --> 01:00:34,902
So we started off by talking about ethics and the fact that there's a feedback.

725
01:00:35,603 --> 01:00:46,521
If you look at your ethics and you begin to behave more beautifully, it has an effect on your general attitude to life, which brings you its insights, that it works.

726
01:00:47,704 --> 01:00:48,105
Even if

727
01:00:48,253 --> 01:00:52,641
Even if people hate you, at least you yourself are peaceful.

728
01:00:53,702 --> 01:00:57,768
I mean, you might be the most peaceful person in the world, full of charisma.

729
01:00:57,789 --> 01:00:59,431
Somebody out there is going to want to shoot you.

730
01:00:59,612 --> 01:01:00,893
I mean, it's just as simple as that.

731
01:01:02,916 --> 01:01:14,514
And there's this other way where we are investigating ourselves, which again brings about a change of attitude and then becomes systemic in the way we behave, the way we think, the way we behave.

732
01:01:15,625 --> 01:01:21,494
So that whole process is one of insight and ethics, and you can't separate them.

733
01:01:21,514 --> 01:01:26,681
And the original ethical stand was falling in love with ourselves.

734
01:01:28,344 --> 01:01:31,429
That's the problem.

735
01:01:31,449 --> 01:01:40,461
And it's coming back to that level and really sort of investigating that sense of presence, a sense of self, which is really cutting to the core of the problem.

736
01:01:40,922 --> 01:01:44,467
And that's exactly what the Buddha found on that wonderful day.

737
01:01:48,463 --> 01:01:53,711
Oh, I can only hope my words have been of some assistance that I have not caused even greater confusion.

738
01:01:53,731 --> 01:02:05,047
That by your devotion to insight, practice, and ethical standards, you may be liberated sooner rather than later.

739
01:02:10,496 --> 01:02:11,958
Can I ask a question?

740
01:02:11,978 --> 01:02:12,079
Sure.

741
01:02:12,099 --> 01:02:14,382
Yeah.

742
01:02:14,402 --> 01:02:15,163
Because earlier on today you said that

743
01:02:18,382 --> 01:02:41,826
I agree with you entirely.

744
01:02:44,422 --> 01:02:47,827
No, it's not a case of getting rid of enjoyment.

745
01:02:47,947 --> 01:02:51,172
It's a case of getting rid of indulgence.

746
01:02:51,271 --> 01:03:03,110
Indulgence means that your sense of happiness is now dependent on preparing food, making sure that somebody's going to eat it, making sure that you like it.

747
01:03:03,471 --> 01:03:04,032
You see what I mean?

748
01:03:04,052 --> 01:03:12,184
There's a whole process of attachment to it whereby you're presuming that when you do this, you're going to feel happy.

749
01:03:12,603 --> 01:03:18,891
And that's different from a spontaneous joy that comes up when you are preparing food for preparing sake.

750
01:03:20,594 --> 01:03:20,695
Yeah?

751
01:03:20,715 --> 01:03:26,222
When you're feeding people just for the sake of feeding people, not to make yourself happy.

752
01:03:26,804 --> 01:03:27,965
I mean, that's the paradox.

753
01:03:28,367 --> 01:03:37,860
The more we do good without thinking of ourselves, the more happiness arises spontaneously and naturally within us.

754
01:03:37,880 --> 01:03:39,382
That's the bit about non-attachment.

755
01:03:39,402 --> 01:03:41,346
That's the bit about non-attachment.

756
01:03:41,365 --> 01:03:41,867
That's it, you see.

757
01:03:42,708 --> 01:03:53,360
And in that, which is slightly more difficult, is, of course, we have to do it for ourselves as well without becoming attached.

758
01:03:55,021 --> 01:04:03,751
So preparing food, say, for ourselves, just by ourselves, is to take a joy in that, right?

759
01:04:03,791 --> 01:04:07,315
Now, if there's a sense of loneliness there,

760
01:04:07,902 --> 01:04:15,449
See, that tells you that for you food isn't enjoyable unless somebody else is talking their heads off and eating at the same time.

761
01:04:16,070 --> 01:04:16,530
You see what I mean?

762
01:04:16,550 --> 01:04:36,170
It's like, yeah, if you can actually sit down and in the same way prepare food very carefully for yourself, for the benefit of your body, and the joy comes up in having treated yourself with kindness, and that's love.

763
01:04:39,610 --> 01:04:44,617
But as I say, these distinctions are very close together.

764
01:04:45,018 --> 01:04:49,105
And we'll never get rid of the attachment until the essential delusion of self disappears.

765
01:04:50,085 --> 01:04:52,909
So you've got to work at it.

766
01:04:55,494 --> 01:05:01,704
But at least we can undermine it by recognizing when that indulgence comes in.

767
01:05:02,545 --> 01:05:07,052
For instance, in relationships...

768
01:05:07,387 --> 01:05:10,090
When does love turn to control?

769
01:05:11,711 --> 01:05:13,574
When does love get confused with control?

770
01:05:15,054 --> 01:05:16,456
It's a really essential point.

771
01:05:17,637 --> 01:05:23,664
Because at the point of control, the other person is no longer a person, they're an object to feed your needs.

772
01:05:25,065 --> 01:05:30,851
So every time you're angry with somebody, bored with them, if they're angry, they're not doing what you want.

773
01:05:30,972 --> 01:05:32,853
If you're bored with them, they're not making you laugh anymore.

774
01:05:33,204 --> 01:05:40,532
And you go through the whole thing of all these negativities and it's all coming from the point of view of this person is here to make me happy.

775
01:05:42,914 --> 01:05:46,699
So you can always tell when the indulgence is not being fed.

776
01:05:47,320 --> 01:05:52,786
The difficulty is knowing when you're feeding the indulgence because it's so close to love and enjoyment.

777
01:05:55,489 --> 01:05:55,969
What a drag.

778
01:06:00,594 --> 01:06:00,974
Very good.

779
01:06:02,356 --> 01:06:03,077
How are we doing for time?

780
01:06:03,648 --> 01:06:06,298
Somebody give me a time slot.

781
01:06:06,740 --> 01:06:06,920
22.8.

782
01:06:06,942 --> 01:06:07,101
22.8.

783
01:06:07,121 --> 01:06:07,804
Oh, that's not bad.

784
01:06:08,929 --> 01:06:13,086
So if we take a break, and then we'll come back and finish the evening off.

785
01:06:13,106 --> 01:06:13,268
Okay.

786
01:06:13,288 --> 01:06:13,387
Okay.

